142 THE ODES OF HORACE

From Phoebus came my pure poetic ᾔτεε, From Phoebus genius and my lyric power: So, therefore, youths, born of illustrious sirae, And virgins, girlhood's flower,

Wards of the Delian Maid who love's to wend With bow in chase of bucks and lynxae fleet‚ Keep time in Lesbian measure and attend My finger’s rhythmic beat,

While duly singing dark Latona's son, And duly Noctiluca's crescent glow, Who speeds the headlong seasons as they run And bids the harvests grow.

Thou, soon a bride, shalt say, “It was my part, When dawned the Secular Festal, to rehearse The song to gods most dear, knowing by heart Horace the poet's verse.”
